+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-19] CR-12-4-P200 [MEDIUM] `manifest_diagnostics` artifact-path prefix guards strip-then-startswith are case-sensitive and `./` evades stripping when used as a character set rather than a string prefix [`eng/release_evidence.py:1129-1137` area] — Edge Case Hunter E1+E2. `normalized.lstrip("./")` treats `'.'` and `'/'` as characters, so `"./nupkgs/Foo.nupkg"` becomes `"nupkgs/Foo.nupkg"` (intended) but `"..//nupkgs/Foo.nupkg"` becomes `"nupkgs/Foo.nupkg"` too (unintended — leading `..` traversal is silently accepted). Separately, the `startswith("nupkgs/")` check is case-sensitive; `Nupkgs/Foo.nupkg` bypasses the unsigned-tree guard. Fix: use `while normalized.startswith(("./","../",".\\","..\\")): normalized = normalized.split(...,1)[1]` and lower-case the prefix check (`normalized.lower().startswith("nupkgs/")`).
+- [x] [Review][Patch][Applied 2026-05-19] CR-12-4-P201 [MEDIUM] `inventory` `<IsPackable>` parse ignores `Condition=` attribute on the property [`eng/release_evidence.py:300-302` area] — Edge Case Hunter E6. A csproj with `<IsPackable Condition="'$(Configuration)'=='Debug'">false</IsPackable>` is treated as unconditionally non-packable; a Release-config-only packable project is misclassified. Fix: skip property elements that carry a `Condition` attribute, OR record both branches and require an unconditional declaration to set `IsPackable`.
